Task 1: Binary Search Tree (BST)Why Inorder is Sorted: In a BST, the left subtree contains smaller values and the right subtree contains larger values. Inorder traversal visits Left -> Root -> Right, naturally resulting in ascending order.Time Complexity: * Average: $O(\log n)$ as each step halves the search space.Worst: $O(n)$ if the tree is "skewed" (like a linked list).Task 2: Graph TraversalBFS vs. DFS: * BFS (Breadth-First Search) explores neighbor by neighbor (level-order) using a queue.DFS (Depth-First Search) explores as far as possible along a branch before backtracking using a stack or recursion.Use Cases: BFS is used for finding the shortest path in unweighted networks; DFS is ideal for cycle detection or solving puzzles.Task 3: Hash TableCollisions: A collision occurs when two different keys result in the same hash index (e.g., $10 \pmod 5 = 0$ and $15 \pmod 5 = 0$).Separate Chaining: This resolves collisions by storing multiple elements in a "bucket" (list) at the same index.Complexity: Average $O(1)$ for lookup; worst $O(n)$ if all keys collide into one bucket.
